I'll start by executing the file_operations_reader tool to read the input data as the first step in the workflow.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll proceed with the next step in the workflow by executing the data_processing_parser to transform the raw data into a structured format.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll handle the error by specifying the input format explicitly in the options parameter for the data_processing_parser tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>

            Since the data_processing_parser tool is not working with JSON format, I'll try using the data_processing_transformer tool to convert the JSON input to a structured format.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "structured",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now I'll proceed with the filtering step using the data_processing_filter tool to process the transformed data.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "source": "data/output.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Finally, I'll execute the data_processing_validator to validate the filtered data and complete the workflow.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": "default",
  "data": "data/output.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll handle the validation error by explicitly specifying the JSON format in the validator options.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": "default",
  "data": "data/output.json",
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>
